caption: We arrived home Thursday night from our 6 day stay which was Wonderful!  Wednesday was a very close second for best dinner. The Pelican Club Restaurant and Bar We were seated promptly and our sweet waitress took our drink order and brought out warm bread. I had the 4 course option which I chose: crab bisque, baked oysters, fried chicken, and bourbon pecan pie (to go) My wife had the pork chop and pecan pie. Everything was great. Beautiful indoor setting ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

The decor was beautiful, and the experience was one I will never forget.

I visited this French Quarter restaurant during a recent trip to NOLA. The seafood-centric menu was eclectic, ranging from fried gulf fish with a sweet and peppery shrimp dressing , to a Massaman Thai curry with shrimp over Jasmine rice. All dishes were scrumptious and generous in their portions. The service was extremely attentive without being intrusive. The ambiance was relaxed and a bit old-school.  By the way, the restaurant participates in the New Orleans Coolinary program and its full menu is available.  This one is a keeper!!

My wife and I came here based on some positive recommendations, and left disappointed with our experience.  The placement of our table was such that the influxes of people waiting at the front were constantly brushing against us. On one occasion someone with their back turned against the table accidentally dipped their jacket into my wife’s dinner, and on a second occasion a different person’s coat touched the top of her wine glass.  If the restaurant owners had an expectation of large groups crowding into the front of the restaurant, they should not be seating people in that spot. Alternatively, the restaurant staff could ask large groups of people to wait at the bar rather than huddled beside an occupied tables.  It was difficult for our server to access us through the mosh pit of patrons waiting to be seated.  I am thankful I finished my entrée before the crowds started surging in, as the lamb was done very nicely. My wife was not so lucky, and did not finish her meal before the crowds arrived!  The meal went from an enjoyable experience to a laughable one. I would not recommend this restaurant.

An unqualified 5-star experience.  My wife and I were in New Orleans and visited the Pelican Club on a Friday night. Despite its proximity to some of the more touristy elements of the French Quarter, it was relatively quiet for the time and day.  We spent just shy of 4 hours here. Jason and Giuseppe were tending bar and did a fantastic job representing the restaurant. We had 5 dishes - Oysters and scallops for apps, whole fish and cioppino for entrees, and a bourbon pie for dessert. The cioppino was a little thicker than they make it in SF (this is a good thing, in my opinion - I dislike the brothy tomato flavor that seems to be embraced out there). Shrimp and scallops were grilled Cajun-style (clear burn marks from the grill) and seasoned very nicely.  Everything was well-executed with an attention to detail. I'd unreservedly recommend this to anyone looking for a quieter place to eat. Prices are not unreasonable at all, though you will pay a bit more here than elsewhere.

The best dinning experience in New Orleans! Our Concierge at Hotel Monteleone recommended several great places for dinner. We ate at all of them and this was the best! We attempted to dine here the night before but opted to wait and try them tonight instead.  The manager relayed to us he was afraid our experience would not be as great as they would like because they were unexpectedly working very short staffed that evening. He did not turn us away but let us decide. We decided to try again later in our trip. He gave us his card for when we came back. I very much appreciated his honesty as I too have worked in the service industry and totally understand his situation. He was so kind and the menu and ambience of the place definitely felt charming and elegant and I knew we would love to try to dine here this trip. Upon our return the next night, the manager remembered us and made our experience there even more wonderful than I’d imagined by treating us to drinks and appetizers! Our waiter and all the staff were so friendly and attentive to every detail. The food was really delicious and the many layers of flavors in each dish were meticulously crafted and presented beautifully.  I enjoyed the baked oysters appetizer and the bread was so good too. Baked oysters are often baked too long and these were perfect. My entree was the Trio of Duckling and my husband enjoyed the Whole Crispy Gulf Fish (Yellow tail snapper)with scallops and shrimp in a citrus chili sauce with rice. I really love duck and anytime I see it on any menu, it means I have to order it and if it is on the menu more than once or different preparations are offered, then I really struggle to decide. That is why this Trio of Ducking is so perfect! I savored every bite of having duck three different ways in one dish! My favorite of the trio was the Asian barbecue duck. It was unique and satisfied an adventurous duck craving I didn’t really know I was missing out on until tonight. The Warm white chocolate bread pudding for dessert was really hard to share with my husband because it was that good! Not too sweet and again it had many layers of flavors working together in each bite that make it hard not to make audible noises of sweet satisfaction. Truthfully, The Pelican Club impressed us all on it’s own outside of the manager’s generosity when we returned. However, it did make our 13th Anniversary even more special that night! The manager and wait staff were outstanding! We will be back for sure! And it’s at the top of our recommendations for our friends and family to experience! I only regret that I did not remember the names of the staff and manager to thank them more personally!

We sat at the bar and Jason, the bartender served up some fantastic drinks and the very best gumbo in New Orleans. This is a must stop for anyone looking for an authentic New Orleans experience. Jason, if I ever start writing that blog I’ll be sure to feature this awesome club...no membership needed.
$$$$ but worth it as a treat.  Our waiter was particularly helpful.
Food was amazing
Jason took care of us from behind the bar and made great recommendations for dinner!
Wonderful meal and service. Great experience!
Great food, Cajun mix
Good food but the service was slow.  Nicer than a lot of places around.  Had large portions.
The best experience for New Orleans quisine. Impeccable
Great!!!!
Nice place, good food

Came in at 9.... Two tables were dirty but empty outside. Told the guy we only wanted to sit outside (because it was a beautiful night) and he said he had two 9:15pm reservations but that he could sit us inside. We then said we only wanted outside and he took down by number and said by 9:30pm if nobody comes, they are yours. We came back at 9:30.... he said he was going to leave them open until close to give them time to come. They never came. He was extremely unprofessional. Tables remained open til close.

I thought this place was just okay for the price. Long tradition and history. Food was good, but not for that price. Service was slower than I would have expected so dinner took way longer than our group anticipated. We were there three hours.
Great niche.  Put it high on your list for N.O. quality dining with atmosphere.
The service was a bit slower than usual. The food was excellent as always. The atmosphere is richly traditional New Orleans. An amazing place.
Food and service were good corkage was high $25
Thank You, Pelican Club for making my mother feel so special on her birthday. Outstanding service and food. My mother could not decide between two deserts and she was given two.

We arrived 5 minutes before our reservation was slated and the staff made us wait another 20 minutes before they could seat us. The place wasn't completely full and there were 3 empty tables for 2 that I spotted during my trip to the bathroom. At the bar, the bartender basically ignored us for 15 minutes until I asked for a menu. The menu had a vegan soup and a vegan entree, so forget about doing prix fixe if you have a dietary restriction involving dairy or fish. The house bread is dusted with parmesan and even though I asked for no cheese and stated that dairy makes me ill, my pasta arrived with cheese. They replaced it quickly, so at least there's that. My companion was treated to overcooked seafood. Rubbery clams, scallops, oysters and crab legs tells me the kitchen is as badly managed as the rest of the place. The decor was nice and the bathrooms were clean, but the nose level was too loud for conversation and the layout didn't offer any privacy or sensation of intimacy. The dishes and drinks were overpriced for what they were. I can't recommend this restaurant for anyone with food allergies or dietary restrictions.
Elegant decor and great food.
Fantastic flounder
A must do in French quartet. Great food. Great service.

We came here on the off-chance, for the restaurant we had chosen was closed on Sundays. Fortunately, for us, this turned out to be fortuitous. The staff were friendly and we had a choice of either dining in the main restaurant, decorated in traditional New Orleans style, or in the bar area which was a little less formal. We chose the latter and had a good window seat and view of what was going on outside. Service was attentive and friendly, but thankfully not overly so. Our waiter provided excellent recommendations and we took his advice. Food was first class...in fact, I'd go so far as to say world class, for we have eaten in really good restaurants all over the world. The flounder was wonderful, as was the bourbon creme brule, but the star (for me) was the gumbo. I don't have a reference point for gumbo, this being the first time I've tried it, but it was delicious and something I would make an effort to seek out if/when we return to New Orleans. I thoroughly recommend this restaurant.
Excellent food, great atmosphere. It was a little hot inside, but overall a wonderful experience.
Love The Pelican Club!
Best place to eat in New Orleans
Great food and friendly staff.  Ate dinner 2 nights in a row at the bar while in town for work. It's a great place to come when they do their restaurant week in August.

It's been quite a while since I dined at the Pelican Club but I plan to remedy that after the fabulous meal I had as part of the WYES dinners.  Food was beautifully presented (fresh seafood presented in a martini glasses!) and the service was excellent.  I plan to go back SOON!!
Not bad. Imperfect service but the food was good
Best meal I had during my trip to New Orleans. Especially loved the gumbo.

I was visiting NOLA for a conference, and met up with a girlfriend for dinner here. Do not expect for this visit to be budge-friendly. However, YOU GET WHAT YOU PAY FOR! The staff was courteous and the service was good too. The Crab Bisque was delicious, as was the scallop stuffed artichoke. My only recommendation to our server was that there should be more artichoke in the dish. My friend enjoyed her filet. We shared the bread pudding and it too, was delicious. I would definitely prepare my  budget for a fancy dinner here next time I am in NOLA.
Excellent dining experience.  Reveillon Dinner was wonderful tonight.
Wonderful reveillon dinner.  The food, service, and ambience were all excellent.
Great food and service was very friendly.
Nice food. Great staff.

Came here for Thanksgiving dinner with my family and I have to say I was somewhat disappointed. This place seems to be really reaching for an immersive fine-dining feel, but there are some holes in the service that left me unwilling to suspend disbelief. Our waiter (a taller, middle aged man who seemed well established at the restaurant) called me sir multiple times, I'm guessing because I have short hair, even after I corrected him (I am very clearly female and was wearing makeup, jewelry and a dress). He was a little rushed and aggressive, even though the restaurant wasn't even half full, and spilled coffee on the table. At least one person's dish for each course was cold when it got to the table, and some plates seemed hastily thrown together, with fingerprints and smudges left on. To me the inconsistencies in the dining room speak to a lack of coordination and leadership in the kitchen. I don't know if this was specific to the prix fixe menu they were doing at the time, but most of our entrees, all different menu items, came out with the same vegetables and components besides the protein, such as bland green beans that could have been out of a can, and some repeats of sauces and purees. It seemed that no thought had been put into the cohesiveness of each individual dish, which leaves the diner feeling like half their plate was an afterthought.  All of this might be acceptable at a more casual and affordable restaurant, but I would expect an establishment like the Pelican Club to have these kinds of things smoothed out, just considering the level of dining they seem to be aiming for. A perfect example is the fact that our server used one of those little crumb scrapers on our table just long enough for someone in our group to comment "oh, fancy!" and then left, leaving most of the table still covered in crumbs. Obviously nobody NEEDS all the crumbs scraped off their tablecloth after every course, but if you're going to go to the trouble to get the scraper out, finish the job. And don't serve half the food cold.  I am only taking the time to write all of this out because I believe that if it gets its act together a little bit, it could have the potential to rival Commander's. A lot of the food (minus the soups, which tasted washed out and fridge-y, and the previously-complained-about green beans) is really, really good. The mushroom ravioli especially knocked it out of the park, even at lukewarm. The escargot were phenomenally classic. I thought the bread pudding couldn't possibly live up to the hype from our server, but it was truly delectable. I think with stronger management in back, a more confident menu, and more thorough service out front, this place could seriously impress me. I look forward to visiting again one day in the future to see if they've figured it out.

Cool place to have dinner & enjoy some new Orleans food! Came here with the family during a brief new Orleans visit, was impressed by the food taste & quality! The portion sizes are on the larger end. However, the service was mediocre & the dishes came out rather slow.
Everything was delicious. The location is great. Not too noisy
The Red Snapper was delicious. But, the service was slow and it was so loud I couldn't here the person next to me.

Reservations are a must, we got lucky upon walking in to just sit at the bar. The clay pot barbecued shrimp and the shrimp and sausage ravioli was delicious! Cocktails were delicious! Staff is friendly and attentive even just the great bar staff!
The food was amazing along with the service. Definitely have to come back here!!!
Great food.
Great service! Ask for Kyra!!!
Best rack of lamb ever!

Food was excellent other than a scallop that was undercooked.  The baked oysters were probably the best we've had.  Flounder was excellent.  The service was okay, nothing special.  Restaurant was loud.
Our little secret in NOLA. It's on our cannot miss list along with commanders palace
OMG!  As good as it gets. Bisque is the finest, and I have never had a higher quality cut of filet. All perfectly prepared and served.

The Pelican Club is now at the top of our list of special places to go. Delightful staff and excellent food. The menu is diverse enough to please anyone. In addition to local seafood standards there are new and creative dishes that take advantage of the best fresh seasonal ingredients. Everything was excellent for our party of four, all of whom have worked in fine dining.

Inattentive maitre d: anyone looking for tables, reserved or not, has to wait for 10 minutes or more. Three parties including ours experienced this. Server also didn't pay attention at any point during the meal: he ordered an incorrect entree and failed to correct the problem, failed to replace broken oil dispenser when notified. Food was fine, but the overall dining experience isn't what we wanted for a romantic night out and certainly isn't worth the money with so many other options around.
Absolutely delicious and the service was outstanding. Thanks Will!
Fantastic food and ambiance. A must for anyone visiting New Orleans. Great for celebrations or after a long day of exploring New Orleans. I also enjoy their bar atmosphere with fabulous cocktails!

Went here on the last night of our honeymoon. The waiter was very nice and quick/attentive even though he was definitely busy. Didn't catch his name but he was very good at his job. The food was also great and the "coolinary" deal was awesome. We will definitely be back if we ever get to come back to NOLA

Had a reservation for a group of 10, the booth seat was messed up so they took care of it swiftly and offered champagne and baked oysters. They dealt with it very professionally. The drinks and food were excellent. I highly recommend the oysters!
Awesome
The food was tasty and the service was friendly and attentive.
awesome bbq shrimp
Slow serving. Very noicy
Outstanding food, drink and service. Great menu. You can't miss w this restaurant
Wonderful place, lovely service. Great wine!
Great venue and service.
Very busy for Valentine's day.
We had a great evening and meal with a large group of friends. The flounder was outstanding. Highly recommend. Great French Quarter experience for a local.

After reading these posts, I would not spend the money for mediocre food and insulting service.   I usually go to NO twice a year, and my sister suggested we give The Pellican a try.  After I looked it up, not on your life would I go.   Never had a bad meal or service at Brennon's or Antoine's.  Maybe their managers know how to run a restaurant, or they have more experience.

Embarrassing.  I had been given a gift certificate by my son who works as a concierge at one of the high end hotels in New Orleans, as a thank you for sending so many hotel guests to The Pelican Club.  Our waitress was from Bulgaria and had an accent.  She also had an little bit of an attitude.   When the bill came we ended up giving her 10% by mistake instead of 20% (she should have gotten 0% because of her bad attitude.)  Long story short she came back to the table and pressed me to answer why we just left her 10% and that the brandy must have made me mess up my numbers!  My God!  I've never had that happen to me before.  Horrible attitude.  I phoned the mgr. and the owner was supposed to phone me but he apparently didn't care enough to bother with it.  This server ruined my and my friend's meal.  Very bad experience. The food is good - but not great.
Better dining experiences ive had in a while.
So good we are there two nights in a row. It is a little expensive relative to the rest of New Orleans
Awsome service
My husband and I sat at the bar and received great service from Bronco. Short rib mashed potato appetizer is fantastic.  Artisan bar is phenomenal.
Seafood martini

Beautiful room. Unfortunately the food was akin to something your served on a flight or a bad cruise. Service was wonderful. Our waitress was lovely. Saw a mouse running across the floor. Not a deal breaker. Mice exist. Just haven't seen one scurry across the floor during service anywhere in a while. We had the prix fixe. The price is right, but again the food does not deliver.
Nice restaurant in an calm area.

Fourth time here. Well kept secret, frequented by locals.  Top notch joint off on a side street. Moderately priced, excellent food.  I love the paneed gulf fish fillet with jumbo lump crabmeat. The combination of dark buttery meunière sauce and touch of creole hollandaise is sublime.  Service has always been great.  The bourbon pecan pie a la mode is a perfect ending. Highly recommended.
Amazing food and drinks. Get the Seafood cioppino

Fantastic dining experience. Recommend baked oysters appetizer. Duck trio entree was life changing! Chocolate cake and bread pudding desserts were OFF THE HOOK! Amazing service! The exec chef/owner came over to introduce himself. Very personable and passionate. Will recommend to friends, and will certainly come back next time we're in town.

Our overall experience here was a moderate one.  We chose to dine at the bar, mostly because we enjoy interacting with our bartenders, however, we were disappointed that our bartender lacked the desire.  Our evening started with the strawberry-lemonade cocktail and a pour of the Old Rip bourbon.  We started with the ahi poke and the baked oysters.  Both nice flavors, balanced.  Our entrees: Seared tuna and scallops and Trio duckling were enjoyable but very mediocre.  Nothing very exciting. The scallops were quite bland and the shredded duck was mushy and boring.  Our desserts: chantilly cake and chocolate cake were very delicious and we quite enjoyed those very much especially with the bottle of Caymus.  Overall with the amount that we spent in money and time, we would have hoped to have had a more interactive service.  We left at closing and the hostess that let us out was very gracious to provide us some wonderful bars to continue our evening.
Awesome food!!!
The Pelican Club is one of our favorite places to eat.  Just a really nice place with great food.

Service was nothing short of bizarre. We wondered if our server was stoned. We had 9 pm reservations on a Friday night and by 10 we were feeling pressured to leave. When we asked for decaf coffee, we were told it would take too long to brew. When we ordered desserts, the waiter suggested we take them to go. ironically, the oft repeated  comment the waiter made throughout our hurried meal was "no problem." BYW, food was ordinary.
The food is good but overpriced and not spectacular. There are better places in French quarter.
Awesome

Restaurant is noisy and seating for two is crowed, sitting next to other patrons.  We asked to move to a larger table and were somewhat rudely told, this is the table for two.  The foods is average, not bad but nothing special.  It's okay if you don't mind being crowded but there are lots of better choices in the same price class.
Amazing innovative cuisine.

Food was strictly average, especially considering the price.  The lobster was tasteless, tough, and rubbery.  The filet steak was adequate at best and the best part about either dish my girlfriend and I had were the sides of green beans and corn.  The desert was nothing special, but passable.  The bisque soup was good, but that's about the only thing that I would rate good.  The service nowhere to be seen for 20-30 minutes, then they would come to the table twice in 5 minutes only not to be seen again for another 20-30 minutes.  Not worth the price or the hassle.  I won't be returning.
Exceptional food in an old New Orleans atmosphere located in the heart of the French Quarter!! Already planning my next visit!
Amazing as always during a recent French Quarter Fest visit! Best escargot in the city, and you can never go wrong with the cioppino.  We took advantage of the perfect weather and dined outside

We dined here at around 7 pm on a Sunday evening.  The chose one of the 4 course meals which include soup, appetizer, entree and dessert.  Both the soups we got were very good.  Our waitress recommended some Oysters for the appetizer and we had that and the crabcake - both were very good.  For entrees we I had their duck and my wife had the lamb, both of which were very good.  The desserts were very good as well.  Overall we both thought the food was very good - the only complaint was that the asparagus was a little salty - but not inedible.  The restaurant is much bigger than it looks - it has several rooms.  We both found the service to be very good.  When our waitress was busy with another table, a different staff member served us - which was much better than letting our food sit around and get cold.  The only other hiccup with our experience was that TPC put us down as a no-show through OpenTable - but that OpenTable resolved that for us.  I wouldn’t hesitate to recommend The Pelican Club for dinner.
This place is always good. It's not cheap, but it is well priced. Loud atmosphere. Incredible service and the food and wine is always up to par. I'd go back.

The food is terrific with a great selection of creole inspired dishes.  The Trio of Duckling: fantastic!  Great service.  The waiter we had was charming and provided some excellent recommendations.  The restaurant is a little difficult to find however the location is fantastic.  Tucked in the French Quarter near art galleries it has the charm and elegance that one would expect in this region.  Only negative it can get noisy when it's busy.

Service was good, albeit slow. Atmosphere was nice, but the food was just average (mediocre) that was fairly bland. I thought the meal was not worth the price. There are much better places in New Orleans, including NOLA, Bayona and August. Try those instead.

Started w/ Shrimp, chicken, andouille gumbo; lt color, plenty meat, wonderful flavor moderately spiced. Wife: seafood martini; me: crab with wild mushroom ravioli,  both outstanding in taste and presentation. Wife: paneed drum w/ jumbo crabmeat, me: LA Cioppino, red sauce over buttery, cheesy linguini; 5 types seafood in it.  Creme Brulee and Choc Decadence cake for dessert, latter served warm. Impeccable service. Super cuisine, great atmosphere.

One word..... ROACHES. We had a party of 10 and a roach ran across the table. We called over a waitor and he said "oh" our waiter seemed un surprised and no one apologized. Later on in the womens restroom sink was another large roach. We stayed to eat b/c we had a large party and the food was ok. Service was defintally lacking.
